-- French Stocks Decline; Air France, Credit Agricole, Steria, Orpea Move
-- B y   S a r a h   J o n e s
-- 2010-10-19T16:16:12Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-19/french-stocks-are-little-changed-air-france-steria-orpea-shares-move.html
France’s CAC 40 Index lost 0.7
percent to 3,807.17 at the close in Paris. The broader SBF 120
Index also fell 0.7 percent to 2,839.17. The following is a list
of companies whose shares either rose or fell in the French
capital. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Air France-KLM Group  (AF FP) gained 0.7 percent to 12.75
euros as Credit Suisse Group AG raised its recommendation for
Europe’s largest airline to “neutral” from “underperform,”
citing an increase in September volumes for the industry.  Alcatel-Lucent SA  (ALU FP) and  Cap Gemini SA  (CAP FP) paced
technology companies lower, falling 3.5 percent to 2.55 euros
and 2.1 percent to 37.17 euros respectively. The shares fell as
Apple Inc. forecast earnings that missed analyst estimates and
International Business Machines Corp. reported a drop in new
contracts.  Credit Agricole SA  (ACA FP) gained 0.6 percent to 11.74
euros, as Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and bank of America Corp.
released third-quarter earnings excluding one-time items that
topped analyst estimates.  Natixis SA  (KN FP) increased 2.5
percent to 4.51 euros and  Societe Generale SA  (GLE FP) increased
1.7 percent to 43.06 euros.  Separately, the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision said
banks will have until 2015 to fully implement rules on how much
cash and liquid securities they must hold to gird against a
funding shortage in a crisis. The committee also said it would
review to make sure they aren’t too onerous.  Groupe Steria SCA  (RIA FP) dropped 9.2 percent to 21.02
euros as Gilbert Dupont downgraded the shares to “add” from
“buy.” The computer-services company said it expects full-year
revenue growth of about 1 percent on a like-for-like basis.
Revenue in the third quarter rose 8 percent to 402.8 million
euros.  Orpea SA  (ORP FP) rallied 3 percent to 35 euros, the
highest level since September 2008, after France’s largest
commercial retirement-home operator raised its 2011 sales target
to 1.21 billion euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
